{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480948"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:54:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:54:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"128"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/128"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.07,0.3,0.48,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"128"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110415"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/128"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"128"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92679"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"2757"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9884"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41997"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110415"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a one hour of epigastric pain, vomiting, sweating and shortness of breath. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes and hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis blood pressure is 135/70 mmHg and pulse 78/min.  An ECG at the time of his presentation shows ST-segment elevation in leads II, III and aVF with ST-depression in I and aVL. He is given aspirin, ticagrelor, sublingual nitroglycerin and subcutaneous enoxaparin and planned for percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst he is being moved for the PCI, he suddenly collapses and becomes dizzy. His blood pressure is now is 80/40 mmHg and his pulse 38/min. A repeat ECG shows P-waves that are dissociated from the QRS complexes with wide QRS complexes. He is given 2 mg of atropine without significant improvement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the best immediate next step in the management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Defibrillation","I/V amiodarone","Synchronised cardioversion","Transcutaneous pacing","I/V lignocaine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDizziness, syncope and severe bradycardia with dissociation of P-wave from QRS complex and wide QRS complex on ECG are suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete heart block/third-degree heart block.\u003C/strong\u003E Complete heart block and other brady-arrhythmias are commonly associated with the \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior wall myocardial infarction,\u003C/strong\u003E this is because of the occlusion of the right coronary artery that also supplies the \u003Cstrong\u003ESA node\u003C/strong\u003E and other parts of the heart\u2019s conduction system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe best step in the management of a complete heart block is to place a \u003Cstrong\u003Etemporary pacemaker via a transcutaneous approach\u003C/strong\u003E and look for the underlying cause, such as coronary ischaemia. In the scenario described, hypotension and instability often demand emergent management with intravenous pharmacotherapy often using atropine boluses or infusions of adrenaline/ isoprenaline. While these therapies are often attempted, they typically result in a limited or transient effect on the heart rate and blood pressure, necessitating escalation to transcutaneous pacing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough treatment of the underlying pathology may result in resolution of complete heart block, transcutaneous pacing may need to graduate to a permanent pace maker for definitive management of persistent heart block.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefibrillation\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Eis not the best immediate next step as it is reserved for patients with shockable rhythms that include ventricular fibrillation and ventricular tachycardia that is non-responding to the medical treatment. This patient\u0027s ECG shows P-waves that are dissociated from the QRS complexes with wide QRS complexes that suggest a complete heart block.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EI/V amiodarone\u003C/strong\u003E is a class-3 anti-arrhythmic drug that is primarily reserved for arrhythmias like\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular tachycardia\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Eand is of no benefit in patients with complete heart block.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynchronised cardioversion\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is used for tachyarrhythmias like ventricular tachycardia, supraventricular tachycardia, and fast atrial fibrillation that are not responding to medical treatment. It is of no use in cases of complete heart block.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EI/V lignocaine\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended for ventricular tachyarrhythmias like ventricular tachycardia, ventricular fibrillation and premature ventricular beats, it is of no use in patients with complete heart block.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inferior wall myocardial infarction is commonly associated with bradyarrhythmias including complete heart block.","Although initial management of complete heart block in haemodynamically unstable patients may include intravenous agents (atropine, adrenaline or isoprenaline), transcutaneous pacing is recommended as complete heart block is typically resistant to pharmacotherapy."],"references":["Deal N. Evaluation And Management Of Bradydysrhythmias In The Emergency Department. Emergency Medicine Practice. 2013; 15:1-15.","ANZCOR Guidelines - Guideline 11.9 - Managing Acute Dysrhythmias: https://www.anzcor.org/home/adult-advanced-life-support/guideline-11-9-managing-acute-dysrhythmias/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92679"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"128"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92679"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T20:12:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T20:12:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"128"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110415"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66